This report presents the results of the traffic impact analysis (TIA) conducted for a proposed mixed-use
development to be located on the iStar site in San Jose, California. The 76-acre site is located in the
Edenvale area of San Jose, adjacent to the Hitachi campus, and situated between SR 85 and Monterey
Road. The proposed project would consist of a mix of up to 720 residential dwelling units, up to 154,000
square feet (s.f.) of retail space and associated 16-pump gas station, and up to 260,000 s.f. of office
space. The project also includes shifting the 450,000 s.f. of retail space and 1 million s.f. of R&D space
that previously was approved for the iStar site to alternative locations within Edenvale Area 2 (area
bounded by SR 85, Monterey Road, Bernal Road, Santa Teresa Boulevard, and Cottle Road). Access to
the site would be provided via Great Oaks Boulevard, Raleigh Road, and Via del Oro.
Since the proposed project will require a change in the General Plan land use designation for the site, a
General Plan Amendment (GPA) long-range traffic analysis was prepared. In addition, since the Edenvale
Area Development Policy (EADP) does not include any provision for allowing traffic from residential or
commercial development within the Redevelopment Area, the EADP will need to be modified or updated
to allow the residential and commercial development that is being proposed as part of the project.
This study was conducted for the purpose of identifying potential traffic impacts related to the proposed
development. The impacts of the project were evaluated following the standards and methodologies set
forth by the City of San Jose and the Santa Clara Valley Transportation Authority (VTA). Since the project
would generate more than 100 peak hour gross vehicle trips, an analysis in accordance with the VTA’s
Congestion Management Program (CMP) guidelines was prepared. The traffic analysis determined the
traffic impacts of the proposed development on 42 key signalized intersections and 9 freeway segments
in the vicinity of the project site during the weekday AM and PM peak periods of traffic.
After applying the City of San Jose trip rates and all applicable trip reductions, constructing up to 720
residential units, up to 154,000 s.f. of retail space and associated 16-pump gas station, and up to 260,000
s.f. of office space on the iStar site would generate 17,794 daily vehicle trips, with 1,175 new trips
occurring during the AM peak hour and 1,688 new trips occurring during the PM peak hour. Using the
inbound/outbound splits recommended by the City of San Jose, the project would produce 687 inbound
and 488 outbound trips during the AM peak hour, and 791 inbound and 897 outbound trips during the PM

The project would not have an adverse effect on existing transit, bicycle or pedestrian facilities in the
Assuming the existing local bus service would remain unchanged with five bus lines and two shuttles
providing service to the Santa Teresa LRT station, LRT service providing trains every 15-minutes, and
Caltrain providing commuter train service (northbound AM and southbound PM) to the Blossom Hill
Caltrain station, the estimated number of new transit riders during the AM and PM peak commute periods
could be accommodated by the available ridership capacity of these existing transit services. Therefore,
no improvements to the existing transit services would be necessary with the project.
The project plans to provide color-accented bike lanes along Great Oaks Boulevard and Raleigh Road,
which will improve bicycle travel in the study area. The color treatment will increase visibility and, thus,
enhance bicycle safety near the project site. Also, a pedestrian bridge will provide bicyclists with a safe
way to cross the railroad tracks and Monterey Road to access the Blossom Hill Caltrain station. The
project-sponsored improvements will not conflict with existing or planned bicycle facilities.
The project will construct sidewalks on Via del Oro north of the SR 85 overpass to accommodate walking
trips between the LRT station and the project site. Furthermore, the project plans to extend Via Del Oro
northward through the site in order to provide a pedestrian “spine” street. The new internal street will
bisect the site and serve as a residential gateway to the Santa Teresa LRT station. The ultimate network
of sidewalks in the vicinity of the project site would provide good connectivity between the site and other
points of interest, and would serve the anticipated pedestrian demand.

that previously was approved for the iStar site to alternative locations within Edenvale Area 2 (area
bounded by SR 85, Monterey Road, Bernal Road, Santa Teresa Boulevard, and Cottle Road). Access to
the site would be provided via Great Oaks Boulevard, Raleigh Road, and Via del Oro. The project site
and surrounding study area are shown on Figure 1.
Since the proposed project will require a change in the General Plan land use designation for the site, a

Traffic conditions at the study intersections and on the study freeway segments were analyzed for the
weekday AM and PM peak hours of traffic. The AM peak hour of traffic is generally between 7:00 and
9:00 AM, and the PM peak hour is typically between 4:00 and 6:00 PM. It is during these periods on an
average weekday that the most congested traffic conditions occur.
Traffic conditions were evaluated for the following scenarios:
Existing Conditions. Existing AM and PM peak hour traffic volumes were obtained from
the City of San Jose and supplemented with new manual turning-movement counts
Existing Plus Project Conditions. Existing plus project peak hour traffic volumes were
estimated by adding to existing traffic volumes the additional traffic generated by the
project. Since approval of the new iStar project requires an update to the Edenvale
Area Development Policy (EADP) to allow additional residential development in
Edenvale Area 5, the project also involves shifting the 450 KSF of retail space and 1
MSF of R&D space that previously was approved for the iStar site to alternative
locations within Edenvale Area 2. Existing plus project conditions were evaluated
relative to existing conditions in order to determine the effects the project would have on
the existing roadway network with any improvements proposed by the project.
Background Conditions. Background traffic volumes were estimated by adding to
existing peak hour volumes the projected volumes from approved but not yet completed
developments. The added traffic from approved but not yet completed developments
was provided by the City of San Jose in the form of the Approved Trips Inventory (ATI).
Note that the estimated traffic that would be generated by the previous entitlements for
the iStar site (450 KSF of retail + 1 MSF of R&D) is included in the City’s ATI.
Background Plus Project Conditions. Projected peak hour traffic volumes with the
project were estimated by adding to background traffic volumes the additional traffic
generated by the project. Since approval of the new iStar project requires an update to
the Edenvale Area Development Policy (EADP) to allow additional residential
development in Edenvale Area 5, the project also involves shifting the 450 KSF of retail
space and 1 MSF of R&D space that previously was approved for the iStar site to
alternative locations within Edenvale Area 2. Accordingly, traffic generated by the
previous entitlements for the iStar site were subtracted from the background traffic
volumes before the project trips were added. The background plus project scenario
evaluates the combined effects of the new proposed project on the iStar site and
relocation of the previous entitlements (450 KSF of retail + 1 MSF of R&D) relative to
background conditions in order to determine potential project impacts, according to the
City of San Jose and CMP Significant Impact Criteria.
Cumulative Conditions. Cumulative near-term traffic conditions were represented by
background plus project conditions plus traffic generated by pending developments.
The traffic generated by pending developments was provided by the City of San Jose.
This traffic scenario was evaluated in order to fulfill the CEQA requirements.
As described above, approval of the new iStar project requires an update to the Edenvale Area
Development Policy (EADP) to allow additional residential development in Edenvale Area 5. Last updated
in June 2006, the EADP is made up of 5 distinct areas. Edenvale Areas 1, 3 and 4, located east of US
101, make up the New Edenvale Industrial Area. Edenvale Area 2, Old Edenvale, is the area bounded by
SR 85, Monterey Road, Bernal Road, Santa Teresa Boulevard, and Cottle Road. Edenvale Area 5,
known as the Mixed-Use Development Area, includes the iStar site and is the area bounded by Monterey
Road, SR 85 and Cottle Road. The EADP was adopted to provide for the timely approval of up to 5 MSF
of R&D/industrial development in the Edenvale Redevelopment Project Area, and acknowledges that
significant congestion will occur at major gateway locations (i.e., US 101/Blossom Hill Road-Silver Creek
Valley Road and US 101/Hellyer Avenue interchanges) until major roadway improvements are
constructed in the future. The Policy allows the level of service at the US 101/Blossom Hill Road-Silver
Creek Valley Road and US 101/Hellyer Avenue interchanges to deteriorate to traffic levels below the
existing acceptable levels identified in Council Policy 5-3, Transportation Level of Service, as an interim
condition until improvements to the impacted intersections are constructed to return to a level of service
better than or equal to the background traffic conditions identified in the EADP once the planned
improvements are constructed for the EADP area.
In addition to build-out of the industrial square footage in the New Edenvale Redevelopment Area (Areas

i.b: Analysis Methodologies and Level of Service Standards

page.text: Traffic conditions at the study intersections were evaluated using level of service (LOS). Level of Service
is a qualitative description of operating conditions ranging from LOS A, or free-flow conditions with little or
no delay, to LOS F, or jammed conditions with excessive delays. The various analysis methods are
The City of San Jose level of service methodology for signalized intersections is the 2000 Highway
Capacity Manual (HCM) method. This method is applied using TRAFFIX software. The 2000 HCM
operations method evaluates signalized intersection operations on the basis of average control delay time
for all vehicles at the intersection. Since TRAFFIX is also the CMP-designated intersection level of service
methodology, the City of San Jose methodology employs the CMP default values for the analysis
The proposed project is subject to the City’s Transportation Level of Service Policy for areas outside the
Downtown Core Area. The City of San Jose level of service standard for signalized intersections is LOS D
or better. The correlation between average control delay and level of service is shown in Table 1.
The designated level of service methodology for the CMP also is the 2000 HCM operations method for
signalized intersections, using TRAFFIX. The only difference in level of service standards is that the City
of San Jose standard is LOS D or better, and the CMP level of service standard for signalized
intersections is LOS E or better. In addition to the LOS E standard for CMP intersections, it is important to
emphasize the CMP standard is not the City of San Jose’s significance impact criteria. Intersections that
do not meet the CMP standard are considered “out of conformance” and not significantly impacted.

The basis of the analysis is as follows: (1) the Poisson probability distribution is used to estimate the 95
percentile maximum number of queued vehicles per signal cycle for a particular movement; (2) the
estimated maximum number of vehicles in the queue is translated into a queue length, assuming 25 feet
per vehicle; and (3) the estimated maximum queue length is compared to the existing or planned
available storage capacity for the movement. This analysis thus provides a basis for estimating future left-
turn storage requirements at signalized intersections.

would occur on 95 percent of the signal cycles. Or, a queue length larger than the 95
would only occur on 5 percent of the signal cycles (about 3 cycles during the peak hour for a signal with a
60-second cycle length). Therefore, left-turn storage pocket designs based on the 95
length would ensure that storage space would be exceeded only 5 percent of the time. The 95
queue length is also known as the “design queue length.”
The remainder of this report is divided into seven chapters. Chapter 2 describes existing conditions
including the existing roadway network, transit service, and existing bicycle and pedestrian facilities.
Chapter 3 presents the intersection operations under existing plus project conditions and describes the
method used to estimate project traffic. Intersection operations under background conditions are
described in Chapter 4. Chapter 5 presents the intersection and freeway operations under background
plus project conditions and describes the project’s impact on the near-term transportation system.
Chapter 6 describes non-level of service operational issues associated with the proposed project.
Chapter 7 presents the long-range traffic impacts on the transportation system associated with the iStar
site General Plan Amendment. Chapter 8 presents the conclusions of the traffic impact analysis.
This chapter describes the existing conditions for all of the major transportation facilities in the vicinity of
the site, including the roadway network, transit service, and bicycle and pedestrian facilities. Also included
are the existing levels of service of the key intersections and freeway segments in the study area.
Regional access to the project site is provided by US 101, SR 85, and Monterey Road.
US 101 is an eight-lane freeway (three mixed-flow lanes and one HOV lane in each direction) in the
vicinity of the site. US 101 extends northward through San Francisco and southward through Gilroy.
Access to and from the site is provided via full interchanges at Bernal Road/Silicon Valley Boulevard,
Blossom Hill Road/Silver Creek Valley Road, and SR 85.
SR 85 is a predominantly north-south freeway that is oriented in an east-west direction in the vicinity of
the project site. It extends from Mountain View to south San Jose, terminating at US 101. SR 85 is a six-
lane freeway with four mixed-flow lanes and two HOV lanes. SR 85 provides access to the project site via
interchanges at Bernal Road and Great Oaks Boulevard.
Monterey Road (SR 82) is a six-lane major arterial north of Blossom Hill Road and a four-lane major
arterial south of Blossom Hill Road. Monterey Road extends from Market Street in downtown San Jose to
US 101 south of the City of Gilroy. Monterey Road provides access to the project site via interchanges at
Bernal Road and Blossom Hill Road.
Major arterials within the project study area include Santa Teresa Boulevard, Bernal Road/Silicon Valley
Boulevard, and Blossom Hill Road/Silver Creek Valley Road. These roadways are described below.

Traffic conditions were observed in the field to identify existing operational deficiencies and to confirm the
accuracy of calculated levels of service. The purpose of this effort was (1) to identify any existing traffic
problems that may not be directly related to level of service, and (2) to identify any locations where the

Overall the study intersections operate well during the AM and PM peak hours of traffic, and the level of
service calculations accurately reflect actual existing traffic conditions. However, field observations
revealed that some minor operational problems currently occur that may not be reflected in the
intersection level of service calculations, as indicated below.

i.b: Cottle Road at Concord Drive and Poughkeepsie Road

page.text: The northbound left-turn movement at this intersection (on-ramp from Cottle Road to Blossom Hill Road)
is heavy during both the AM and PM peak hours of traffic. As a result, the northbound vehicle queues on
Cottle Road occasionally extend south past Poughkeepsie Road. When this occurs, vehicles are forced to
stop so as not to block the intersection. At times, it takes two signal cycles for all queued northbound
vehicles to clear the Cottle Road/Poughkeepsie Road intersection due to the backup.
During the AM peak hour, the southbound left-turn movement into Kaiser San Jose Medical Center
experiences very high traffic volumes. As a result, the southbound left-turn vehicle queue occasionally
spills out of the left-turn pocket. However, since the southbound left-turn movement is served twice during
each signal cycle, it typically only takes one cycle for all queued vehicles to clear the intersection.
During the AM peak hour, the northbound left-turn vehicle queue frequently spills out of the left-turn
pocket. However, the green time for this movement is sufficiently long to allow all vehicles to clear the
intersection in one signal cycle and no operational issues occur.

i.b: Blossom Hill Road Overpass at US 101/Monterey Road

page.text: Blossom Hill Road has two travel lanes in both the eastbound and westbound directions on the Monterey
Road and US 101 overpasses. During the AM peak hour, the vast majority of vehicles are traveling
eastbound on Blossom Hill Road toward the US 101 ramps. Thus, the demand for the rightmost
eastbound through lane is greatest along this segment of Blossom Hill Road.
The Blossom Hill Road/Monterey Road overpass has an auxiliary lane that is utilized by vehicles merging
onto eastbound Blossom Hill Road from the Cottle Road/Concord Drive ramp, and by vehicles exiting
Blossom Hill Road to Monterey Road. The short (350-foot) auxiliary lane slows the flow of traffic on
Blossom Hill Road and the ramp from Cottle Road/Concord Drive as a result of the weaving process.
A second identical weaving area exists further east on Blossom Hill Road involving vehicles merging onto
eastbound Blossom Hill Road from Monterey Road and vehicles exiting eastbound Blossom Hill Road to
southbound US 101. The 300-foot auxiliary lane slows the flow of traffic on Blossom Hill Road and the
ramp from Monterey Road as vehicles weave in and out of the lane. In addition, the vehicle queues on
eastbound Blossom Hill Road due to the AM metering lights at the US 101 northbound loop on-ramp
extend onto the US 101 overpass. As a result, some vehicles make u-turns at the Blossom Hill
Road/Silver Creek Valley Road intersection in order to bypass the loop on-ramp and instead enter
northbound US 101 via the diagonal on-ramp from westbound Blossom Hill Road.
During the AM peak hour, the vehicle queue for the SR 85 northbound loop on-ramp occasionally extends
back past the Bernal Road/SR 85 intersection. However, the light turns red for the northbound movement
on Bernal Road at approximately the same time the queue reaches the intersection. Once the light turns
green, the vehicle queue at the loop on-ramp has dissipated and there is space for all vehicles that were
stopped at the signal to proceed and enter the queue. Thus, the vehicle queue for the SR 85 northbound
loop on-ramp does not create any operational issues.
During the AM peak hour, the vehicle queue for the SR 85 northbound diagonal on-ramp occasionally
extends past the US 101 southbound off-ramp. When this occurs, the off-ramp is blocked momentarily.
However, this is only temporary and does not result in significant queuing on the US 101 southbound off-
ramp, and all vehicles are able to exit the freeway off-ramp without a significant amount of delay.

This chapter describes existing plus project traffic conditions, including the method by which project traffic
is estimated. Existing plus project traffic conditions could potentially exist if the project was constructed
and occupied prior to the other approved projects in the area. It is unlikely that this traffic condition would
occur, since other approved projects expected to add traffic to the study area would likely be built and
occupied during the time the project is going through the development review and construction process.
Existing plus project conditions ignores any potential traffic from prior approvals and does not include any
planned and funded roadway improvements that have not been constructed.

text.b: Transportation Network Under Existing Plus Project Conditions

page.text: It is assumed in this analysis that the transportation network under existing plus project conditions would

project, then the iStar project would be required to construct four lanes between Manassas Road and SR
85. The iStar project would add bike lanes and sidewalks to this segment of Great Oaks Boulevard.
Via del Oro Upgrade – The City has indicated that the project will be required to upgrade the segment of
Via del Oro that passes under SR 85 and continues to the north toward the project site to public street
standards, which includes the addition of sidewalks. Upgrading this segment of Via del Oro will require

Raleigh Road Extension – The project would connect Raleigh Road to Via del Oro and Great Oaks
Boulevard. The new street would bisect the project site and would have an 84-foot right-of-way with bike
lanes. The project would install one new traffic signal at Great Oaks Boulevard/Raleigh Road and a traffic
Coronado Avenue – The project would construct a new street to provide access to the retail component of
the project. Coronado Avenue would have a 64-foot right-of-way with bike lanes. As described above, the
project proposes to construct a traffic circle (roundabout) at the Coronado Avenue/Raleigh Road

The magnitude of traffic produced by a new development and the locations where that traffic would
appear are estimated using a three-step process: (1) trip generation, (2) trip distribution, and (3) trip
assignment. In determining project trip generation, the magnitude of traffic entering and exiting the site is
estimated for the AM and PM peak hours. As part of the project trip distribution, an estimate is made of
the directions to and from which the project trips would travel. In the project trip assignment, the project
trips are assigned to specific streets. These procedures are described further in the following sections.
Trips generated by any new development can be estimated based on counts of existing development of
the same land use type. The City of San Jose has used count data of existing development that has been
collected over the years to derive a list of trip generation rates for the most common land uses. The trip
generation rates that have been developed can be applied to new development within the City to help
predict future traffic increases that would result from the new development. These recommended rates
are detailed in the San Jose Impact Analysis Handbook, August 2008. Therefore, trip generation resulting
from new development proposed within the City of San Jose typically is estimated by multiplying the City’s
established trip generation rates by the size of the development.
A mixed-use development with complementary land uses such as residential/retail and residential/office
will generate and attract trips internally between the uses. Thus, the number of vehicle trips generated for
each use may be reduced, since a portion of the trips would not require entering or exiting the site. The
VTA’s Congestion Management Program Transportation Impact Analysis Guidelines (March 2009)
indicates a trip reduction of up to 15 percent is allowed for residential/retail mixed-use developments and
up to 3 percent is allowed for residential/office mixed-use developments. The reduction is applied to the
smaller of the two complimentary trip generators, and the same number of trips is then subtracted from
the larger trip generator. In addition, since most of the residential component of the mixed-use project is
located within approximately 2,000 feet of the Santa Teresa LRT station, the total number of trips
generated by the residential uses were reduced by 9 percent (VTAs TIA Guidelines). Note that both
mixed-use reductions associated with the residential component of the project were applied to the net
residential trips, which are the residential trips remaining after applying the 9 percent transit reduction.
The project proposes a membership-only gas station as part of the retail component of the project. Based
on reliable data collected by Kittelson & Associates, Inc., a 35 percent shared trip reduction was applied
to account for vehicle trips that would be captured internally due to gas station users that would visit the
associated membership-only retail use in the same trip during the PM peak hour. Although the retail use
would generate some AM peak hour trips, it is assumed that there would be no internal shared trips
between the gas station and retail users during the AM peak hour because the retail use would be closed
to customers in the AM. A 15 percent trip reduction for internal capture was applied to the remaining gas
station trips (net trips after applying the 35 percent shared trip reduction) to account for gas station trips
that would be generated internally due to the residential and office components of the project. The trip
reduction was applied to the gas station generated trips only, since the trips associated with the
residential and office components of the project would occur with or without the gas station.
Note that although the project includes a retail component, no pass-by trip reduction was applied. Trip
generation for retail uses typically are adjusted to account for pass-by-trips. Pass-by-trips are trips that
would already be on the adjacent roadways (and so are already counted in the background traffic) but
would turn into the site while passing by. Justification for applying the pass-by-trip reduction is founded on
the observation that such retail traffic is not actually generated by the retail development, but is already
part of the ambient traffic levels. Since the project site is not located adjacent to a major roadway, the
traffic study conservatively does not apply a pass-by trip reduction.
After applying the City of San Jose trip rates and all applicable trip reductions, constructing up to 720
residential units, up to 154,000 s.f. of retail space and associated 16-pump gas station, and up to 260,000
s.f. of office space on the iStar site would generate 17,794 daily vehicle trips, with 1,175 new trips
occurring during the AM peak hour and 1,688 new trips occurring during the PM peak hour. Using the
inbound/outbound splits recommended by the City of San Jose, the project would produce 687 inbound
and 488 outbound trips during the AM peak hour, and 791 inbound and 897 outbound trips during the PM
peak hour. The project trip generation estimates are presented in Table 5.
The trip distribution pattern for the project was estimated based on existing travel patterns on the
surrounding roadway system and the locations of complementary land uses. The project trip distribution
patterns for the proposed land uses are shown graphically on Figure 6.

This chapter presents background traffic conditions, which are defined as conditions just prior to
completion of the proposed project. It describes the planned transportation system, the procedure used to
determine background traffic volumes, and the resulting traffic conditions. The background scenario
predicts a realistic traffic condition that would occur as approved development gets built and occupied.
At the guidance of the City of San Jose, it was assumed in this analysis that the transportation network
under background conditions would be the same as the existing transportation network with the exception
of some funded improvements associated with the Hitachi Site Master Plan project. Hitachi has been
conditioned to make roadway improvements in conjunction with approval of the Hitachi project. For the
purpose of this traffic study, these required improvements were assumed to be in place for the
background conditions analysis. All of the required roadway improvements that are not already in place
but are planned as part of the Hitachi project are listed below.
SR 85 and Cottle Loop Ramp – A northbound Cottle Road loop on-ramp to northbound SR 85 will be
constructed. This will involve eliminating the left-turn movement from northbound Cottle Road onto
northbound SR 85, eliminating the northbound SR 85 loop off-ramp to southbound Cottle Road, and
adding a signalized westbound approach to the Cottle Road/SR 85 (north) intersection to serve traffic
exiting northbound SR 85 at Cottle Road. The changes will create a signalized T-intersection.
SR 85 and Great Oaks Boulevard (South) – A second eastbound right-turn lane will be added to the
southbound SR 85 off-ramp to Great Oaks Boulevard.
The unfunded Edenvale Area Development Policy (EADP) improvements that are planned for the US
101/Blossom Hill Road-Silver Creek Valley Road interchange are listed below. Although all of the
estimated traffic from the EADP projects is included in the City’s Approved Trips Inventory (ATI),
